From the data information above, we have 60,000 training images and 10,000 test images, each with 784 pixels or features (originally in a 28*28 dimention) whose values range from 0 (black) to 255 (white). The labels data is one dimentional, containing a 0-9 label for each image, which corresponds to each article of clothing.

Data Preprocessing:¶

It is essential to perform feature scaling on the input data prior to model fitting to ensure acurate performance as the values are read by the chosen ML model and to help increase the speed of analysis. This is especially important when the units of your different features are not comparable (in our case however, all of our features are pixel values of roughly the same range 0-255). Here, two data transformation methods will be examined and their performace compared: standardization and normalization. Using norm = 'max' as our argument, out normalization function below will scale the data between 0 and 1 while the standardization function will center the data around an average of 0 and a standard deviation of 1.

In [3]:
#-------- Apply different types of data transformation on X_train and X_test ------
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.preprocessing import Normalizer

# 1. using StandardScaler()
X_train_Scaled = StandardScaler().fit_transform(X_train)
X_test_Scaled = StandardScaler().fit_transform(X_test)

# 2. using Normalizer()
X_train_Norm = Normalizer(norm = 'max').fit_transform(X_train)
X_test_Norm = Normalizer(norm = 'max').fit_transform(X_test)

labels = {0 : "T-shirt/top",
          1 : "Trouser",
          2 : "Pullover",
          3 : "Dress",
          4 : "Coat",
          5 : "Sandal",
          6 : "Shirt",

# creating a function to display randomly selected images as subplots with custom titles
def display_samples(num_images, X_dataset, title='row', y_dataset=None, y_predicted=None):
    '''
    Create a plot with a user given number of subplots which displays randomly selected
    images from the given 2D numpy array dataset. This function also creates custom titles.
    
    Parameters
    ----------
    num_images: int
        How many random images to show
    
    X_dataset: 2D numpy array
        The dataset from which to choose random images. Could be X_train or X_test.
    
    title: string
        'row' (default) to use the randomly selected row number as the subplot title
        'true_label' to use the labels from the user-given y_dataset as the subplot title. Must correspond to X_dataset.
        'predicted_label' to use the 'predicted_label(true_label)' format as the subplot title
    
    y_dataset: 1D array
        The dataset containing the true labels. Could be y_train or t_test. Must be the same length as X_dataset.shape[0]
        
    y_predicted: 1D array
        The dataset containing the predicted labels. Must be the same length as X_dataset.shape[0]
    '''
    
    # create 'num_images' subplots 
    figures, axes = plt.subplots(1, num_images, figsize=(13, 13))
    ax = axes.ravel()

    # select 'num_images' random rows/images from X_dataset and save selected row numbers in a list called 'row'
    # iterating 'num_images' times, select a random number between all possible row indices from X_dataset
    row = list(np.random.randint(0,X_dataset.shape[0]-1) for i in range(num_images))

    for i in range(num_images): # for every image selected above..
        # ..reshape the row into it's 2D form and convert to greyscale
        ax[i].imshow(X_dataset[row[i]].reshape(28,28), cmap = 'gray')
        
        # for the title..
        if title == 'row': 
            ax[i].set_title(f"Image #{row[i]}") # .. set the plot title from the row number
        
        elif title == 'true_label':
            key = y_dataset[row[i]] # ..get the corresponding y-label from the user-given y_dataset (an integer from 0-9)..
            ax[i].set_title(f"{labels[key]}") # ..and get the title from the label dictionary
        
        elif title == 'predicted_label':
            key_actual = y_dataset[row[i]] # ..get the corresponding true y-label which is an integer from 0-9..
            key_predicted = y_predicted[row[i]] # ..and the corresponding predicted y-label..
            ax[i].set_title(f"{labels[key_predicted]}({labels[key_actual]})") # ..and get the title from the label dictionary

    figures.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

  • As we can notice from the images above, the normalized data does not seem to differ from the original data. This is because the normalization transformation retained the relative distances between the different values since all features shared the same fixed range of 0-255 and simply shifted the range of values from 0-255 to 0-1 as we saw in the histogram plot earlier. However, this might still help increase the speed of the training process.
  • As for the standardized data, we can see that the images generally look different than the original ones. This is because it computes the average pixel value of each feature individually and uses that, along with it's standard deviation, to rescale that feature without any specific min/max value to adhere to.

from sklearn.svm import SVC

# time the data training process, set the number of loops and runs to 1 each
# apply a support vector classifier with linear kernel and regularization of 0.025

# apply svc on X_train_Scaled data

y_predicted_svc_Scaled = my_svc_Scaled.predict(X_test_Scaled)
print(f"Our SVC prediction using X_train_Scaled is {np.sum((y_test == y_predicted_svc_Scaled))/100}% accurate using 10,000 training samples.\n")


# apply svc on X_train_Norm data
%timeit -n1 -r1 my_svc_Norm = SVC(kernel="linear", C=0.025).fit(X_train_Norm[:10000, :], y_train[:10000])

# compare SVC and MLP performance
from sklearn import metrics
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, confusion_matrix

# create a function to display classification report and confusion matrix
def display_metrics(classifier, true, predicted):
    '''
    Create a report summary for the given classifier.
    
    Parameters
    ----------
    classifier: sklearn classifier
        The classifier for which the report will be displayed.
    
    true: 1D array
        The dataset containing the true labels for the test data.
        
    predicted: 1D array
        The dataset containing the predicted labels for the test data, obtained from the same user-given classifier.
        
    '''
    # print the classification report
    print(f"\n---------Classification report for classifier {classifier}-------\n\n"
    f"{classification_report(true, predicted)}")

    # create confusion matrix and display plot
    cm = confusion_matrix(true, predicted)
    plt.figure(figsize = (10,8))
    # obtain the axes values from the label dictionary
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot = True, fmt = '.0f', xticklabels = list(labels.values()), yticklabels = list(labels.values()))
    plt.ylabel('Actual label', fontdict = {'size': 14}); plt.xlabel('Predicted label', fontdict = {'size': 14})
    plt.show()

In all three models we have trained above, the ones that used the standardized training data generally performed the best compared to the ones trained on the original and normalized data according to the quick accuracy check, so for sake of simplicity, the classification reports and confusion matrices will compare only those models.

ML Performance Comparsion:¶

  • Comparing the accuracy scores of our svc classifier and mlp classifier using 10,000 training images, we can see that the scores for our mlp model is more accurate than than our svc model accross all training sets. We can similarly see that training our model using 60,000 images yeilded more accurate results compared to training it with the smaller dataset, with the exception of the normalized training data. In conclusion, our most accurate model is the mlp model trained on the entire standardized training set.

  • Comparing the confusion matrices above, displayed from our standardized datasets, we can observe the proportions of misclassification for each of the nine categories. In all cases, the category with the most misclassification is 'Shirt', often misclassified as 'T-shirt/top', 'Pullover' or 'Coat', which is not an unexpected misclassification. However, the mlp model trained on the entire standardized dataset shows the highest f1-score (0.68) as seen in the classification reports, compared to the svc model (0.57) and the mlp model trained only on the partial dataset (0.63). The f1-score is discussed here since it takes into consideration both precision and recall.

  • With regards to execution time, it seems that for the smaller training data, svc performed faster than mlp. But when considering the entire dataset, mlp performed much faster than svc. In fact, when we trained the svc model on all 60,000 images, it took a relatively significant amount of time (40 minutes and counting) so the execution was interrupted and only 10,000 images were taken into account for svc training. Another point noticed was that, with 10,000 training images, all models using transformed training data performed faster than ones using the original training set.

1. Sobel Filter¶

In [30]:
# create a new training/test set containing X_train/X_test images but with the sobel edge detection applied on each one

# initialize an empty array with the same shape as the original array to store the output
X_train_sobel = np.empty(X_train.shape)
X_test_sobel = np.empty(X_test.shape)

# set the desired sobel parameters
ddepth = cv2.CV_64F  # 64-bit float output
dx = 1  # first-order derivative in x-direction
dy = 0  # no derivative in y-direction

# apply sobel edge detection on X_train
for image in range(X_train.shape[0]): # for each row/image..
    sobel = cv2.Sobel(X_train[image,:].reshape(28,28), ddepth, dx, dy) # ..reshape and apply the sopel filer..
    X_train_sobel[image] = sobel.reshape(784)# ..unshape and save row back to output array
    
# apply sobel edge detection on X_test
for image in range(X_test.shape[0]):
    sobel = cv2.Sobel(X_test[image,:].reshape(28,28), ddepth, dx, dy)               
    X_test_sobel[image] = sobel.reshape(784)

# create a new training/test set containing X_train/X_test images but with the bilateral filter applied on each one

# initialize an empty array with the same shape as the original array to store the output
X_train_bilat = np.empty(X_train.shape)
X_test_bilat = np.empty(X_test.shape)

# apply bilateral filter on X_train
for image in range(X_train.shape[0]): # for every row/image.
    bilat = cv2.bilateralFilter(X_train[image,:].reshape(28,28),9,85,85) #.. reshape and apply bilaterl filer..
    X_train_bilat[image] = bilat.reshape(784) #..unshape and save in output array
    
# apply sobel edge detection on X_test
for image in range(X_test.shape[0]):
    bilat = cv2.bilateralFilter(X_test[image,:].reshape(28,28),9,85,85)               
    X_test_bilat[image] = bilat.reshape(784)

  • Comparing the accuracies of our mlp model using both X_train and X_train_Scaled in three different conditions: without any image modification, with sobel edge detection and with bilateral filtering, we can see that the most accurate model remains that of the standardized data without any modifications to it. Applying the sobel edge detection on the standardized data seems to not affect the accuracy much, but applying the bilateral filter led to decrease in accuracy. As for using X_train on our mlp model, both modifications lowered the accuracy compared to no image modification.

  • Looking at the confusion matrices and taking 'Shirt' again as an example for assessing misclassification, the sobel edge detection input led to less misclassification using the standardized training set (recall: 0.71) compared to the bilateral filtering (recall: 0.59) using the same dataset. This is even better than the recall score without image modification (recall: 0.63) as seen in the confusion matrix in Q4. Recall is discusssed here to see how many out of the true 1000 T-shirt images were predicted correctly.
